            <ce:date-received day="23" month="10" year="2024"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="1" month="9" year="2025"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="3" month="9" year="2025"/>
            <ce:abstract id="ab0010" class="author" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="abs0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0070" view="all">Conversion of natural forests to managed forests has reduced the amount of older, structurally diverse forests worldwide. In coniferous forests of the Pacific Northwest (USA), where understory plants represent 90 % of the species but only 1 % of forest biomass, the long-term impacts of timber harvesting remain unclear. We investigated these impacts by remeasuring a chronosequence of forests in the Siskiyou Mountains, Oregon, initially sampled in 2003. In 2021, we resurveyed 13 plots (2500 m² each), ranging from 25 to 445 years in age, to assess changes in the relationship between age, canopy cover, environmental attributes, and multiple measures of understory diversity in early-seral logged stands compared to mature and old-growth conditions. Over the 18-yr period, canopy cover increased in early-seral stands (20 %), which transitioned into canopy closure, leading to an average loss of 11 species per plot, declines in early-seral indicator species, and increased compositional similarity to mature stands. Beta diversity was highest in early-seral stands and declined with stand age, a pattern that remained consistent across sampling periods. In old-growth stands, increases in a few shade-tolerant species drove declines in evenness and diversity, a pattern that partially aligns with expectations of increased plant cover under rising temperatures and reduced precipitation. These findings offer insight into legacy effects of clearcut logging and potentially climate change on a critical component of forest biodiversity: plantations have entered a phase of canopy closure, low species richness, and reduced diversity, while species diversity and evenness have also declined in old-growth stands.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords id="keys0005" class="keyword" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="key0005">
                  <ce:text>Clearcut logging</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0010">
                  <ce:text>Richness</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0015">
                  <ce:text>Understory vegetation</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0020">
                  <ce:text>Plant community</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0025">
                  <ce:text>Non-metric multidimensional scaling ordination</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0020">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Data will be made available on request.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0005" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">The global conversion of natural forested lands to managed forests has occurred largely through timber harvesting and, in many cases, the subsequent establishment of tree plantations. Of the world’s 4.1 billion ha of forested areas remaining in 2020, 66 % have been logged at least once (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0085" refid="bib29">FAO, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Currently, 294 million ha of these logged forests are planted, and of those, 45 % are intensively managed plantations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0090" refid="bib29">FAO, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The impact of this conversion on the structure and diversity of biological communities has been the subject of numerous studies over the past few decades (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0005" refid="bib65 bib66 bib97">Kusumoto et al., 2015; LaManna and Martin, 2017; Seedre et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Several earlier investigations have used a chronosequence approach to compare the plant community composition in logged (managed) stands with those of older, unmanaged stands. These and other studies generally found that understory richness increases after stand-replacing disturbance due to an influx of ruderal, early-seral species, then declines with canopy closure, as shade-intolerant species are lost (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0010" refid="bib43 bib47 bib57 bib87 bib90 bib92 bib96 bib111">Halpern and Spies, 1995; Hermy and Verheyen, 2007; Jules et al., 2008; Poudel et al., 2019; Roberts and Gilliam, 1995; Rybar et al., 2023; Schoonmaker and McKee, 1988; Ujházy et al., 2017</ce:cross-refs>). These empirical studies are consistent with conceptual models of stand development following stand-replacing disturbance that predicted increasing richness in recently established forest stands, a decline in richness to its lowest levels during canopy closure, and an increase in richness with understory re-initiation during forest maturation (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0015" refid="bib32 bib44 bib100">Franklin et al., 2002; Harris et al., 1982; Spies and Franklin, 1991</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Factors that underly species responses and recolonization after logging are related to sensitivity to canopy closure and changes in abiotic conditions, including the mode of seed dispersal, microsite availability, and vegetative persistence (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0020" refid="bib42 bib72 bib79 bib103">Halpern and Lutz, 2013; Loehle et al., 2021; Meier et al., 1995; Su et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Dispersal limitation is an important driver of re-colonization following logging, provided suitable habitat conditions are available (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0095" refid="bib26">Ehrlén and Eriksson, 2000</ce:cross-ref>). Early-seral plant communities often have a high proportion of wind dispersed shade-intolerant species that colonize sites with open canopy conditions and low levels of litter. However, understory species that have deeply buried underground organs capable of resprouting, such as rhizomes and corms, that survive the process of logging and are often capable of resprouting in the Pacific Northwest, USA. As a result, these communities can retain 75–90 % of the pre-disturbance species following disturbance(<ce:cross-ref id="cr0100" refid="bib39">Halpern, 1988</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0105" refid="bib43">Halpern and Spies, 1995</ce:cross-ref>). However, many of these same species decline during periods of canopy closure, especially shade-intolerant species that require open conditions for establishment and reproduction (Lezberg et al., 1999), and the longer-term impact of timber harvest on understory vegetation is still not fully understood.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">In the Pacific Northwest, federally managed National Forests experienced timber harvesting and subsequent planting that lasted over 40 years. From the mid-1950s until policy changes with the Northwest Forest Plan in the early 1990s, primary forests were clearcut on federal lands and most often replanted with seedlings of a single conifer species, typically Douglas-fir (<ce:italic>Pseudotsuga menziesii</ce:italic> Mirb. Franco) (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0025" refid="bib48 bib51">Hirt, 1995; Johnson et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Previous studies in the Pacific Northwest suggest that plant diversity returns to pre-disturbance levels 20–30 years after logging with increasing species richness and fluctuating species heterogeneity before entering canopy closure, though some plant species may require more time to recover (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0030" refid="bib43 bib64 bib96">Halpern and Spies, 1995; Kreyling et al., 2008; Schoonmaker and McKee, 1988</ce:cross-refs>). In the western region of the USA, according to data published in 2014, 31 % of forest stands on National Forest lands are now less than 60 years old at that time (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0110" refid="bib84">Oswalt et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Given that many managed forests are still relatively young, full recovery of understory plant composition may not yet have occurred. This is particularly significant because while the understory plant community comprises only 1 % of the biomass in Pacific Northwest conifer forests, it represents 90 % of the plant species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0115" refid="bib36">Gilliam, 2007</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">In addition to legacies of past management, there is growing concern that a warming climate may alter understory communities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0035" refid="bib58 bib79 bib116">Jump and Peñuelas, 2005; Meier et al., 1995; Walck et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>). The impact of climate change on plant communities in mountainous regions are expected to vary depending on factors such as aspect, slope, soil characteristics, and elevation (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0040" refid="bib13 bib19 bib91">Case et al., 2021; Damschen et al., 2010; Rumpf et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). In their analyses of plant communities in the Siskiyou Mountains of northern California and southwest Oregon, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0120" refid="bib19">Damschen et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref> observed xerification of community composition over a 56-year period (1956–2007) in lower elevations (400–1200 m), while <ce:cross-ref id="cr0125" refid="bib45">Harrison et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref> observed increases in relative cover by species of northern biogeographic affinity at higher elevations (1500–2100 m). The suppression of the natural fire regimes since the early 20th century has led to loss of open-canopy conditions through an increased density of shade-tolerant trees that is also impacting understory plant communities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0045" refid="bib2 bib10 bib56 bib62">Abella and Springer, 2015; Brodie et al., 2023; Jules et al., 2022; Knapp et al., 2013</ce:cross-refs>) and could potentially influence the effects of warming.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">We utilize permanent plots established across a chronosequence of forest ages in the Siskiyou Mountains (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0050" refid="bib57 bib59 bib120">Jules et al., 2008; Kahmen and Jules, 2005; Whittaker, 1960</ce:cross-refs>). Plots were initially sampled in 2003 to assess the relationship between plant species composition and stand age. In 2003, understory species richness was highest in early-seral stages (7–44 years; termed “early seral” from hereon), lowest in middle-aged stands experiencing canopy closure (40–60 years; termed “mature” from hereon), and intermediate to high in the stands with late successional characteristics (complex stand structure, large old trees, and high volume of coarse woody debris; 90–427 years; termed “old growth” from hereon) (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0055" refid="bib57 bib100">Jules et al., 2008; Spies and Franklin, 1991</ce:cross-refs>). We resampled these plots and examined many of the same relationships in stands that are now 18 years older to test the prediction about the effects of canopy closure, a structural change occurring across large portions of the Pacific Northwest landscape, on multiple aspects of plant diversity.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The objective of this study was to assess the changes in diversity and trajectories of understory plant communities and stand conditions (i.e., canopy cover) over an 18-year period across a chronosequence of stand ages. We focus on losses and gains of species and the subsequent effects on multiple, interrelated metrics of species diversity. We examine species richness (number of species), evenness (a measure of distribution of abundance among species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0130" refid="bib86">Pielou, 1966a</ce:cross-ref>), Shannon diversity (a measure of diversity incorporating both the richness and evenness; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0135" refid="bib74">Magurran and McGill, 2011</ce:cross-ref>), and beta diversity (variation in species composition among sampling units; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0140" refid="bib4">Anderson et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0145" refid="bib121">Whittaker, 1972</ce:cross-ref>). We compare these metrics among developmental stages (early seral, mature, and old growth) within and across each sample year (2003 and 2021) in relation to stand age and structure (i.e., canopy cover, diameter of largest trees, forest floor components). Across the entire chronosequence, we hypothesize that the community composition of the early-seral forests would shift toward that of mature stands, and that the composition of mature stands shifted toward that of old growth. We hypothesized that there would be declines in richness and beta diversity and increases in evenness in the early-seral plots due to losses of shade-intolerant species and increased dominance of shade-tolerant species as canopy cover declines and litter levels increase over time. We hypothesize relative stability in mature and old-growth plots that either gained understory species or maintained similar levels of the different diversity metrics. We also propose an alternative hypothesis in response to warming where understory communities decline in richness and beta diversity and increase in evenness as drought sensitive species are lost, leaving a few dominant, drought tolerant species and a more homogenous community.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0010" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0030">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0035">Study site</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Our study was conducted in the Siskiyou Mountains of southwestern Oregon, a mountain range within the Klamath ecoregion between the western Coast Range and the southern Cascades. The Siskiyou Mountain region is floristically diverse due to complex soil parent materials and steep climatic gradients (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0060" refid="bib16 bib94 bib120">Coleman and Kruckeberg, 1999; Sawyer, 2007; Whittaker, 1960</ce:cross-refs>). In the late 1940s and early 1950s, Robert Whittaker laid the foundation for understanding the interaction between plant communities and the complex geology and topography of the Klamath ecoregion and provided a description of these communities within the old-growth forests (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0150" refid="bib120">Whittaker, 1960</ce:cross-ref>). Whittaker’s research was immediately followed by extensive clearcutting that persisted until the early 1990s (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0155" refid="bib51">Johnson et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). National Forest lands in the Siskiyou Mountains underwent the same history of clearcutting as elsewhere in the Pacific Northwest, resulting in a fragmented landscape of clearcuts, plantations, and remnant older forests (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0065" refid="bib55 bib112">Jules, 1998; USDA Forest Service, 1995</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">Our study plots are in, or immediately adjacent to, the Sucker Creek watershed (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0160" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>), a 250 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> drainage that experiences cold, wet winters and warm, dry summers. Elevations range from 1372 m to 1494 m. The average annual precipitation for the 30-year period of 1992–2022 in the study area was 1605 mm with seasonal mean temperatures ranging from 3 ℃ in January to 18 ℃ in July (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0165" refid="bib88">PRISM Climate Group, 2023</ce:cross-ref>). A trend of increasing temperatures and decreasing precipitation is evident between the sampling years. In 2021, the precipitation was 433 mm lower, the mean temperature for the growing season was 3 ℃ higher, and the winter minimum temperature was 1.6 ℃ higher (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0170" refid="bib88">PRISM Climate Group, 2023</ce:cross-ref>; Appendix: <ce:cross-ref id="cr0175" refid="sec0110">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0180" refid="sec0110">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Forest communities in our study area range from dry and warm Douglas-fir (<ce:italic>Pseudotsuga menziesii</ce:italic>)/tanoak (<ce:italic>Notholithocarpus densiflorous</ce:italic>) communities to mesic and cool/wet white fir (<ce:italic>Abies concolor</ce:italic>)/Douglas-fir (<ce:italic>Pseudotsuga menziesii</ce:italic>) communities with occasional Shasta red fir (<ce:italic>Abies magnifica</ce:italic> var. <ce:italic>shastensis</ce:italic>) at higher elevations (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0070" refid="bib3 bib120">Agee, 1991; Whittaker, 1960</ce:cross-refs>). Common species in the understory layer include herbs such as trail plant (<ce:italic>Adenocaulon bicolor</ce:italic>), vanilla leaf (<ce:italic>Achlys triphylla</ce:italic>), anemone (<ce:italic>Anemone deltoidei</ce:italic>), starry false Solomon's seal (<ce:italic>Maianthemum stellatum</ce:italic>), and western trillium (<ce:italic>Trillium ovatum</ce:italic>), and shrubs such as wood rose (<ce:italic>Rosa gymnocarpa</ce:italic>), California blackberry (<ce:italic>Rubus ursinus</ce:italic>), and snowberry (<ce:italic>Symphoricarpos albus</ce:italic>) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0185" refid="bib15">Christy et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">The historical fire regime in the Siskiyou Mountains was characterized by frequent, mixed-severity fire that resulted in dynamic fine-scale mosaic of open and closed-canopy conditions (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0075" refid="bib3 bib105">Agee, 1991; Taylor and Skinner, 1998</ce:cross-refs>). Fire scar records from 1480 to 1989 indicate a median fire-return interval of 15.5–25.5 years (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0080" refid="bib3 bib105">Agee, 1991; Taylor and Skinner, 1998</ce:cross-refs>). From the 1960s until the early 1990s, 34 % of the late-successional forests were clearcut and replanted with Douglas-fir seedlings (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0085" refid="bib51 bib112">Johnson et al., 2023; USDA Forest Service, 1995</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0040">Study design</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">Data for this study were collected in 2021 in the same stands sampled in 2003 by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0190" refid="bib57">Jules et al. (2008)</ce:cross-ref>. These included six young stands (age 7–44 years in 2003) initiated by clearcut logging and planting of Douglas-fir and nine older unmanaged stands (four mature 90–130 years and five old growth 170–427 years in 2003). We resampled 13 of the original 15 plots and omitted two that were logged or burned since 2003. Plots were selected to be as comparable as possible in their environmental characteristics, and all were restricted to non-ultramafic parent soils (diorite or metasedimentary rock). In addition, all plots were located on west- to northwest-facing aspects (264°-328°) between 1295 and 1495 m elevation, had an average slope between 9 % and 30 %, and were at least 60 m from the nearest road or clearcut edges. Ages of the managed stands were determined by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0195" refid="bib59">Kahmen and Jules (2005)</ce:cross-ref> based on time since broadcast burning or, if a site was not burned, time since clearcut harvest. Broadcast burning is the controlled application of fire to remove leftover woody debris after timber harvest and to clear competitive vegetation in preparation for replanting. The ages of the unmanaged stands were estimated from ring counts of increments cores taken from the 10 largest trees in each stand (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0200" refid="bib59">Kahmen and Jules, 2005</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0045">Data collection</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">In 2021 we followed the sampling protocols of <ce:cross-ref id="cr0205" refid="bib57">Jules et al. (2008)</ce:cross-ref>. The abundance of understory vegetation was assessed using 20 evenly spaced 2 m radius circular subplots within the 50 × 50 m permanent plots. Although the plots were marked with permanent corner posts, the subplots were not permanently marked, and we reestablished them using 50 m tapes in the field in 2021. Subplots perimeters were delineated by installing pin flags at 2 m from the center point in each of eight directions. The vascular plants within these subplots were recorded and their percentage cover estimated for all species ≤ 3 m tall as 0.5 %, 1 %, or in increments of 5 % between 5 % and 100 %. Many of the pin flags from the original survey were still present after 18 years, which increased our confidence in the repeatability of our sampling locations. The data were collected in the early summer of 2021, June 6th – July 4th, and in midsummer, July 19th – August 8th to account for different plant phenologies. For analyses, the cover estimates from the midsummer sampling were used except when the species had senesced; in these instances, estimates from the early summer sampling were used (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0210" refid="bib57">Jules et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). Nomenclature followed the Jepson’s manual (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0215" refid="bib7">Baldwin and Goldman, 2012</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">The 13 forest stands were grouped into three development stages based on the age of dominant trees in 2003; early seral (ES, <ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 5), mature (M, <ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 3), and old growth (OG, <ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 5; <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0005"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0220" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). We retained the original developmental stage classification for all sites in 2021. Several components of live and dead structure were measured in the field to assess structural changes between sampling periods. Tree canopy cover above each subplot was estimated using a spherical densiometer held at breast height. Subplot values were used to estimate the mean and variability (SD) of canopy cover in each plot. In addition, the following stand structural characteristics were recorded for each subplot: percent cover of coarse woody debris 7–15 cm (CWD 1) and ≥ 15 cm (CWD 2) diameter, bare mineral soil, and litter and duff depth (cm). The diameter at breast height (DBH) was measured for the ten largest trees and all snags (standing dead trees) ≥ 6.5 DBH (cm) in each plot.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Although plots were selected to be as comparable as possible in their abiotic conditions, we accounted for additional topographic variation by computing an index of heat load, HLI (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0225" refid="bib77">McCune and Keon, 2002</ce:cross-ref>)—a measure of solar radiation. HLI is a function of slope, aspect, and latitude and ranges from 0 (on cool, northeast-facing aspects) to 1 (on warm, southwest-facing aspects). Topographic parameters for each plot were obtained from a Digital Elevation Model raster and the ‘hli’ function within the raster, terra, and spatialEco R packages (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0230" refid="bib76">McCune et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0235" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0050">Univariate analysis of changes in species diversity metrics and canopy cover</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">To calculate species richness, Pielou’s evenness, Shannon diversity, and beta diversity, we used the vegan and betapart R package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0240" refid="bib83">Oksanen et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0245" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Species richness, calculated using the ‘specnumber’ function, represents the total number of assumed species present in a plot. Pielou’s evenness, derived from the ‘diversity’ function, measures how evenly cover is distributed among the species in a plot, with values ranging from 0 (uneven) to 1 (completely even) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0250" refid="bib86">Pielou, 1966a</ce:cross-ref>). Shannon diversity, also calculated using the ‘diversity’ function, considers both species richness and evenness of a plot, with higher values indicating greater diversity.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">Beta diversity measures the variation in species composition among sites. In our study we use it to assess the variation in species composition among subplots within each plot to understand how heterogeneity in species composition differs among developmental stages and at different time periods. The Bray-Curtis index was used to quantify the dissimilarity among all pairs of subplots based on species abundance, with values ranging from 0 (completely similar) to 1 (completely dissimilar). Beta diversity was computed for each plot in each year (26 measures) using the function ‘betadisper’ and ‘bray.part’, which reduces these Bray-Curtis dissimilarities to principal coordinates to allow for the calculation of distances to centroids in a Euclidean space (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0090" refid="bib8 bib68 bib83">Baselga and Orme, 2012; Li et al., 2023; Oksanen et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0255" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Beta diversity increases as heterogeneity in species composition within plots increases.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">For each response variable, we used a paired Wilcoxon signed rank test to assess the change between sampling dates in each of three development stages; Bonferroni-adjusted P values were used to account for the multiple comparisons of stages. We used the ‘wilcox.test’ function from the stats R package (R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0260" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). To test differences among developmental stages in each sampling year we used the Kruskal Wallis tests employing the ‘kruskal.test’ function from the stats R package (R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0265" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Dunn post hoc tests with Bonferroni adjustments for multiple comparisons were applied where there were significant results. These multiple comparisons were made using the 'dunnTest’ function in the FSA R package (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0270" refid="bib22">Dinno, 2023</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0275" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). In addition to the community metrics, we were interested in the structural changes (e.g., canopy cover, duff and litter depth, cover of coarse woody debris) of these forest plots and how these relate to the ecological community. In our analysis, we performed these statistical tests using plot averages to assess changes over time. We considered p-values less than 0.05 as statistically significant, and results with p-values between 0.05 and 0.10 were considered marginally significant, indicating potential trends that might benefit from further investigation.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0035" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0055">Generalized additive mixed-effects models</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">The relationship between stand attributes and understory vegetation was assessed by developing Generalized Additive Mixed Effects Models (GAMMs) using the ‘gamm’ function in the mgcv and gratia R packages (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0280" refid="bib98">Simpson, 2024</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0285" refid="bib123">Wood, 2017</ce:cross-ref>). These models were used to predict species richness, Pielou’s evenness, Shannon diversity, and beta diversity across forest development stages using subplot-level data. Explanatory variables included stand age, canopy cover, duff and litter depth, average DBH of the largest trees, cover of coarse woody debris (CWD) classes 1 and 2, and interactions of these variables with sample year, to evaluate whether their influence changed between 2003 and 2021. Variables for bare mineral soil cover and snag density were excluded due to high correlations with other predictors. Stand age and the diameter of the largest trees were highly correlated, leading to concerns of concurvity in GAMMs. However, since both variables were ecologically meaningful and of independent interest, we built separate models for each to avoid multicollinearity and enable clearer interpretation of their individual effects.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">HLI was included as a covariate in all models to account for environmental variation among plots. Subplot was modeled as a random effect to account for potential shifts in subplot location between sampling years. We specified k = 4 for smooth terms, based on a priori expectation that the response variables would vary gradually across three forest development stages. To reduce the risk of overfitting due to outlying values, we applied the cubic regression spline with shrinkage basis ("cs") to the CWD variables, which penalizes unnecessary sinuosity and allows smooth terms to shrink toward zero when not supported by the data. This basis dimension allowed enough flexibility to capture transitions while minimizing the risk of overfitting. Diagnostic checks using ‘gam.check’ indicated that this value of k was sufficient.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.6</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0060">Ordination and multivariate analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">To assess whether species composition differed among developmental stages (early seral, mature, and old growth) within sample year and between the 18-year sampling period, a non-metric multidimensional scaling (NMDS) ordination was conducted using the ‘metaMDS’ function in the vegan package in R (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0290" refid="bib83">Oksanen et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0295" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). We chose NMDS ordination because it is effective for assessing compositional differences when data are non-normal (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0300" refid="bib76">McCune et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). The species matrix used in this analysis had 123 understory species that were square-root transformed and relativized by total plot cover to down-weigh the importance of dominant species, which can mask the contributions of subordinate species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0305" refid="bib56">Jules et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Bray-Curtis was used as a measure of dissimilarity. The stress of the ordination was not improved by dropping rare species in the species matrix; therefore, all species were included. The visual representation of the final ordination used centroids for each developmental stage with standard error ellipses with a 95 % CI. Pearson correlations were computed to characterize the relationships between the stand attributes (stand age, canopy cover, canopy standard deviation, HLI, CWD, bare mineral soil, litter and duff depth, snag count, and mean DBH of 10 largest trees) and plot scores along the ordination axes.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">In addition to the NMDS, we ran permutational analyses of variance (PERMANOVA) to test whether species composition differed among the three developmental stages by testing the main effects of developmental stage, sample year, and their interaction. We used the functions ‘adonis2’ from the vegan R package and ‘pairwise.adonis’ for post hoc comparison of the significant effects using the pairwiseAdonis R package. Both tests were run with 999 permutations and individual Bonferroni <ce:italic>P</ce:italic>-value adjustments for multiple comparisons (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0310" refid="bib75">Martinez Arbizu, 2017</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0315" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">To explore whether shifts in species' shade tolerance strategies were associated with changes in canopy cover, we conducted an ordination analysis of community composition across plots. By overlaying species' shade tolerance scores onto the ordination space, we assessed whether community structure aligned with a shade tolerance gradient, thereby linking canopy dynamics to functional community responses. This second ordination was run with 50 permutations using subplot-scale data for all plots over both sampling dates (520 samples in total) to assess how heterogeneity in composition had changed between 2003 and 2021 within plots. As with the first ordination, species cover data were square-root transformed and relativized to subplot totals. A trait matrix of shade tolerance for the understory plant species was created to combine with the ordination to determine if there was a pattern in shade tolerance within the community composition of plots. The species were categorized by shade tolerance (high, intermediate, and low) and species were plotted at their maximum abundance in the ordination. Trait information for each plant species was obtained from descriptions in USDA Plants Database and Fire Effects Information System (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0095" refid="bib110 bib113">U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023; USDA NRCS, 2023</ce:cross-refs>). The visual representation of the final ordination used centroids that represent the average position of the subplot points for each plot in the reduced-dimensional space, while the ellipses are based on the standard error with a 95 % CI. Pearson’s correlation between selected stand attributes (stand age, canopy cover, canopy variation, and HLI) and the ordination axes were assessed.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0045" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.7</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0065">Indicator species analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">To aid in the interpretation of the NMDS analyses, we conducted an Indicator Species Analysis (ISA) with species data from each year (2003 and 2021). We used the function ‘multipatt’ from the indicspecies R package, employing the ‘IndVal’ function with 999 permutations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0320" refid="bib11">Cáceres and Legendre, 2009</ce:cross-ref>; R <ce:cross-ref id="cr0325" refid="bib17">Core Team, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The Indicator Value (IV) is calculated as the square root of the product of specificity (A; proportion of a species, <mml:math altimg="si0001.svg">
                           <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math>, total abundance in a particular developmental stage, <mml:math altimg="si0002.svg">
                           <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math>) and fidelity (B; the proportion of developmental stages, <mml:math altimg="si0003.svg">
                           <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math>, where the species, <mml:math altimg="si0004.svg">
                           <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                        </mml:math>, is found) and scaled to 100 for interpretability. The IV is maximum (1.0) when all individuals of a species are found in a single developmental stage and when the species occurs in all plots of that stage.<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="eqn0005">
                              <mml:math altimg="si0005.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi>I</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ndVal</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mn>100</mml:mn>
                                    <mml:mo>×</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msqrt>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mo>×</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>g</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:msqrt>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                     </ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0050" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0070">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0055" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0075">Changes in canopy cover, structural attributes, and species diversity metrics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">We found a marginally significant increase in canopy cover in the early-seral plots (72 % in 2003, 92 % in 2021), but no significant change in the mature (87 % in 2003, 90 % in 2021) or old-growth plots (82 % in 2003, 88 % in 2021) (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0010"/>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-refs id="crs0100" refid="tbl0010 tbl0015">Tables 2 and 3</ce:cross-refs>, <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0330" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). Although the canopy cover was significantly lower in early seral than in mature stands in 2003 (72 % vs. 87 %), it did not differ in 2021 (92 % vs. 90 %) (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0105" refid="tbl0010 tbl0015">Tables 2 and 3</ce:cross-refs>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0335" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Among the changes in structural attributes observed in the early-seral stands, there was a marginally significant decrease in the cover of exposed mineral soil and in both size classes of coarse woody debris (CWD) (-4 % bare soil, −4 % CWD 1, −4 % CWD 2). Additionally, there was a marginally significant increase in DBH of the largest trees and in litter depth in early-seral stands (+17.4 cm DBH, +0.6 cm litter). In the mature stands, no significant changes in structural attributes were detected between sample years. In the old-growth stands, the only marginally significant change was a decrease in duff depth (-0.6 cm duff; Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0340" refid="sec0110">Fig. S2-S6</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0345" refid="sec0110">Table S2-S3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">In 2003, early-seral stands had significantly fewer snags than old-growth stands and significantly higher percent cover of exposed mineral soil. By 2021, these differences were no longer significant. There were also fewer snags in early-seral stands compared to mature stands in 2003, along with a higher cover of exposed mineral soil; however, this trend was weakly significant and was no longer observed in 2021. In both sample years, duff depth and the DBH of the largest trees remained significantly lower in early-seral stands compared to old-growth stands (Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0350" refid="sec0110">Fig. S2-S6</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0355" refid="sec0110">Table S2-S3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">Species richness declined 21 % in the early-seral plots from 2003 to 2021, with an average loss of 11 species per plot, while it was unchanged in the mature and old-growth plots (average loss of 1 species per plot; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0360" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0365" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). In 2003, the mean richness of the early-seral plots (57 species) was not significantly different from that of the old-growth plots (51 species; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0370" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). However, it was significantly higher than in the mature stands (41 species). By 2021, there were no differences among developmental stages (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0375" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0380" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">Evenness did not change in early-seral or mature stands, but there was a marginally significant decline in old growth (0.73 in 2003, 0.67 in 2021; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0385" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0390" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). There was a marginally significant decline in diversity in the 18-year period in the early-seral and old-growth stands (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0395" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0400" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). The decline in diversity was greater in the early-seral than in the old-growth plots (11 % vs 6 %; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0405" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0410" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). There were minimal changes in beta diversity in all developmental stages (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0415" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>). In both years, beta diversity was greater in early-seral than in old-growth plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0420" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0425" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0080">Effects of stand age, canopy cover, and stand attributes on species diversity metrics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">Forest structural variables significantly influenced biodiversity metrics, with several effects varying between 2003 and 2021. Species richness increased with stand age in both years and exhibited a U-shaped relationship with the DBH of the largest trees, with the lowest richness occurring in stands where the largest trees had intermediate DBH values (40–80 cm). In 2003, richness declined with increasing litter depth, and in 2021, it declined with increasing canopy cover. Richness also showed a weakly significant decline with increasing cover of CWD 2 in 2021 (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> = 0.067; <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0430" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0435" refid="sec0110">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">Evenness decreased significantly with canopy cover in 2003 and showed a sigmoidal relationship with the DBH of the largest trees in 2021, peaking around 40–50 cm and declining around 90–110 cm. Shannon diversity increased with stand age and followed a U-shaped trend in 2021, with lower diversity in stands aged 100–200 years. A similar U-shaped pattern emerged in relation to the DBH of the largest trees in 2021, with reduced diversity in stands where large trees averaged 50–90 cm DBH. In 2003, diversity showed weak trends of increasing with stand age and large tree DBH, and decreasing with canopy cover (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0440" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0445" refid="sec0110">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">Beta diversity generally declined with increasing stand age in both years, indicating lower compositional heterogeneity in older stands. It also declined with increasing litter depth and cover of intermediate-sized coarse woody debris (CWD 7–15 cm). In contrast, the cover of large CWD (&gt;15 cm) contributed to a gradual increase in beta diversity. However, the widening confidence intervals at higher CWD cover values suggest increased uncertainty in the prediction, likely due to fewer observations in that range. While this limits the strength of inference in the upper end of the gradient, the overall trend remains informative. In both years, beta diversity decreased with increasing DBH of the largest trees. This trend was linear in 2003 and sigmoidal in 2021, with the highest beta diversity observed in stands where the largest trees were &lt; 50 cm DBH (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0450" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0455" refid="sec0110">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0065" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0085">Multivariate analysis of shifts in species composition and ordination</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">The PERMANOVA results showed that species composition significantly differed among stages, but there was no significant effect of year, or stage × year interaction (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0460" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>). Across developmental stages the early-seral stage is significantly different from mature and old-growth stands (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0465" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>). Although the interaction with stage and year was not significant, a post-hoc analysis of the stages in each year gave further insight that the community composition of the early-seral stage was significantly different from the old-growth stage consistently and was only significantly different from the mature stands in 2003 (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0470" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">The final NMDS ordination of plots had three dimensions selected due to lowest stress value of 0.098 after 500 iterations. The NMDS ordination (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0025"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0475" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>) illustrates the relative stability in community composition of mature and old-growth stands, contrasted with notable changes in early-seral stands. The most pronounced shift in ordination space occurred in the early-seral plots. By 2021, early-seral plots closely resembled mature plots in composition and continued to overlap with their 2003 counterparts. This overlap likely reflects the influence of Plot 1 (25 years post-clearcut), which retained characteristics typical of more recently harvested plots sampled in 2003 (e.g., less canopy cover and lower DBH). In contrast, the composition of mature and old-growth plots remained relatively stable over the 18-year period (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0480" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">The first NMDS axis was positively correlated with stand age, percent canopy cover, duff and litter depth, number of snags, and tree DBH, and negatively correlated with canopy cover variation and bare mineral soil (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0025"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0485" refid="tbl0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>). The second axis showed negative correlations with percent canopy cover, HLI, and litter depth (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0490" refid="tbl0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0495" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>). The NMDS ordination with species traits by shade-tolerance (high, intermediate, and low), had a five-dimensional solution with a stress of 0.118 after 50 iterations. Axis 1 was positively correlated with stand age and negatively correlated with HLI (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0030"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0500" refid="tbl0030">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0030"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0505" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>). Axis 2 was positively correlated with canopy variation (SD) and negatively correlated with percent canopy cover (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0510" refid="tbl0030">Table 6</ce:cross-ref>). Species with greater shade tolerance showed greater abundance lower on axis 2 in plots with greater canopy cover and higher on axis1 in plots of greater age. Conversely, species with limited shade tolerance showed the greatest abundance in early-seral plots. Finally, species with intermediate shade tolerance were distributed in intermediate positions in the ordination space (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0515" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0070" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0090">Indicator species analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">We found a general trend of a lack of indicator species in mature stands, and many indicators for early-seral and old-growth stands, though with a marked reduction in the number of species indicative of early-seral stands after the 18-year period. Species of low and intermediate shade tolerance (i.e., <ce:italic>Ceanothus velutinus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Chamerion angustifolium</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Elymus glaucus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Penstemon anguineus</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Rubus ursinus</ce:italic>) were associated with early-seral stands in 2003 and were no longer associated with any distinct developmental stage in 2021. <ce:italic>Sambucus racemosa</ce:italic> (a perennial species with intermediate shade tolerance that grows in areas of open canopy and is capable of rhizomatous reproduction) is the only species that remained a significant indicator of the early-seral stage in 2021, though with a weaker association (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0035"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0520" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>). The geophyte, <ce:italic>Chimaphila menziesii</ce:italic>, is a rhizomatous low-growing subshrub that indicates low light conditions and was weakly associated with mature stands in 2003 and in 2021 was significantly associated with early-seral stands (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0525" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">There were no significant indicator species for the mature plots in either sample year. It is worth noting that <ce:italic>Amelanchier alnifolia</ce:italic>, a relatively short-lived moderately shade-tolerant shrub, was associated with mature stands in both sample years with a weaker association in 2021. There were eight significant indicator species for old-growth stands in both sample years (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0530" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>). Most species persisted as indicators in 2021 except for two orchids, the myco-heterotrophic orchid, <ce:italic>Corallorhiza maculata</ce:italic>, and the hemicryptophytic orchid, <ce:italic>Goodyera oblongifolia</ce:italic>. Conversely, two shade-tolerant perennial herbs, <ce:italic>Anemone deltoidea</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Lysimachia latifolia</ce:italic>, were significantly associated with old-growth stands in 2021. Of the persistent indicators, the strongest association were the shade-tolerant herbs <ce:italic>Maianthemum stellatum</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Clintonia uniflora</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Adenocaulon bicolor</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0535" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0075" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0095">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">Our study adds to a growing body of work that demonstrates how past land management and succession influence understory vegetation, and in particular for the unique plant communities in the Siskiyou Mountains (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0110" refid="bib19 bib45 bib55 bib57 bib59 bib80 bib85 bib104">Damschen et al., 2010; Harrison et al., 2010; Jules, 1998; Jules et al., 2008; Kahmen and Jules, 2005; Mills, 1995; Palladini et al., 2007; Tallmon et al., 2003</ce:cross-refs>). Our findings, based on long-term forest plot change in naturally regenerated and logged stands, provide insights into the dynamics occurring at both the forest stand and broader landscape levels. These results indicate that forests harvested in the late 20th century have entered a species-depauperate stage of forest development with canopy closure. Our study supports the model of stand dynamics for temperate coniferous forests that depicts high understory species richness in early-seral stands (e.g., replanted clearcut sites), followed by a decline in richness to its lowest levels during canopy closure, and then another increase in richness with forest maturation and transition towards old-growth (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0115" refid="bib32 bib44 bib57 bib100">Franklin et al., 2002; Harris et al., 1982; Jules et al., 2008; Spies and Franklin, 1991</ce:cross-refs>). Furthermore, our study shows that though canopy cover has a significant influence on richness, it is not the only influence, and other aspects of stand structure (i.e., DBH of large trees, litter depth) may be predictors of understory richness. In addition, our results document the decline of species evenness and diversity in old-growth stands over nearly two decades.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">Although the study system we used continues to build on a body of information about the impacts of timber harvesting, chronosequence studies have limitations. One fundamental assumption is that all sites share the same type of initiating disturbance, but frequently this is not the case (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0120" refid="bib31 bib52 bib117">Foster and Tilman, 2000; Johnson and Miyanishi, 2008; Walker et al., 2010</ce:cross-refs>). In our study, young stands were initiated by clearcut logging and broadcast burning, while older stands were most likely initiated by wildfire or experienced multiple fires of varying severity. However, the primary goal of our study was to understand whether managed forests with different disturbance histories (i.e., clearcuts) were recovering on a trajectory towards those stands without a history of management (i.e., naturally regenerated stands), or if managed stands were on potentially divergent trajectories. In addition, while most chronosequence studies sample at a single time, our study is unique because it includes two samples 18 years apart. This approach provided clearer insight into understory dynamics by comparing rates of change across different stages of forest development over an approximately twenty-year time frame. By using repeated measurements, the study captured actual temporal changes rather than relying on the assumptions of space-for-time substitutions typical of chronosequence studies (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0125" refid="bib31 bib117 bib125">Foster and Tilman, 2000; Walker et al., 2010; Yanai et al., 2000</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec0080" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0100">Recent changes in understory plant communities</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">Species richness was strongly associated with stand age, structural attributes (DBH of largest trees), and canopy cover (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0540" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>), along with litter depth and cover of bare mineral soil (Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0545" refid="sec0110">Fig. S6</ce:cross-ref>). The previously open canopy plots (early-seral developmental stage) in this study lost an average of 11 species per plot over an 18-year period as they entered canopy closure, reaffirming the prediction of <ce:cross-ref id="cr0550" refid="bib57">Jules et al., (2008)</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0555" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>. The results align with previous studies showing a general pattern where species richness initially increases after disturbance due to greater light and soil resource availability, then declines as tree size and competition increase and canopy closure excludes shade-intolerant species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0130" refid="bib42 bib115">Halpern and Lutz, 2013; Vetaas et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). However, the effect of canopy cover on richness is not as significant as the structural features, namely large tree DBH. Stands with smaller trees and those with very large trees had higher levels of richness than stands with tree size typical of mature Doug fir plantations (45 – 90 cm) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0560" refid="bib9">Bingham and Sawyer, 1991</ce:cross-ref>). While the DBH of large trees gives us some insight into the stage of stand structure—smaller trees in early seral, mature plantation diameter, and the largest trees correlated with older stands—further measurements (i.e., tree density, interquartile range of DBH) would need to be made to draw further relationships with stand structure (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0565" refid="bib106">Thom et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">Although plant richness was consistently the lowest in the mature forests, the decrease in richness of early-seral stands in 2021 shifted the richness and stand age pattern from the U-shape (higher richness in ES and OG) to a more linear relationship increasing with stand age (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0570" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>). The decline in diversity and evenness in old-growth stands is likely a result of an increase in cover by a few common, shade-tolerant species (e.g., <ce:italic>Achlys triphylla</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Adenocaulon bicolor</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Chimaphila umbellata;</ce:italic> Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0575" refid="sec0110">Fig. S7</ce:cross-ref>) that tend to be dominant where present and have benefitted from 18-year growth under relatively stable stand conditions (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0135" refid="bib21 bib60 bib62">De Frenne et al., 2013; Kardol et al., 2010; Knapp et al., 2013</ce:cross-refs>). These dominant species have reproductive strategies that enable the establishment of high cover, such as rhizomatous clonal growth (<ce:italic>Achlys triphylla</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Chimaphila umbellata</ce:italic>) and prolific seed dispersal (<ce:italic>Adenocaulon bicolor</ce:italic>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0580" refid="bib25">Dyrness and Acker, 2010</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">Our results on recent changes in old-growth forests align with the longer-term observations of <ce:cross-ref id="cr0585" refid="bib45">Harrison et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref> where sites at higher elevations (&gt;1280 m) experienced an increase in the relative cover of northern-temperate flora (e.g., shade-tolerant and mesic species; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0590" refid="bib46">Harrison and Grace, 2007</ce:cross-ref>). The plots in our study were all at elevations greater than 1280 m and had an observed increase in the abundance of dominant species with northern affinities (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0595" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>; Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0600" refid="sec0110">Fig. S6</ce:cross-ref>). A microclimate effect from dense canopies and multilayered forest structure may buffer the understory plant responses to macroclimate warming in these stands, although there is potential for further declines in evenness and diversity as climate change progresses (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0605" refid="bib19">Damschen et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0610" refid="bib21">De Frenne et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0615" refid="bib33">Frey et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0620" refid="bib60">Kardol et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Our results however, are partially contrary to <ce:cross-ref id="cr0625" refid="bib19">Damschen et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref>, who found that in their diorite soil plots at relatively low elevations ranging 500–1200 m the relative cover of herbaceous species with northern affinities had declined over a 56-year period, while those with southern affinities (low shade tolerance and high drought tolerance; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0630" refid="bib46">Harrison and Grace, 2007</ce:cross-ref>) had increased. While the dominant species in our plots exhibit high shade tolerance, they are not strictly drought-intolerant. For example, <ce:italic>C. umbellata</ce:italic> tolerates dry conditions (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0635" refid="bib110">U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023</ce:cross-ref>) and <ce:italic>A. triphylla</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>A. bicolor</ce:italic> have been documented to withstand drought conditions if populations are already well established (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0140" refid="bib7 bib118">Baldwin and Goldman, 2012; Waring, 1969</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">Climatic conditions during the 18-year sampling period were markedly warmer and drier, with a reduction of 433 mm in annual precipitation and an increase of 3°C in mean growing season temperature (Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0640" refid="sec0110">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0645" refid="sec0110">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). These shifts may have contributed to observed changes in forest floor components, but despite these climatic changes, stand structure and composition in our study plots have remained relatively undisturbed. This stability may be contributing to the overall stability of beta diversity across developmental classes. In a study of thermophilization of understory species by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0650" refid="bib102">Stevens et al. (2015)</ce:cross-ref>, they found that sites with less disturbance or with lower severity disturbance retained higher proportion of northern-temperate flora, even at lower precipitation levels. Furthermore, they suggested that low and intermediate disturbance increased beta diversity, whereas stands with a lack of disturbance had lower beta diversity and those that experienced high-severity disturbance had the lowest beta diversity (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0145" refid="bib89 bib102">Roberts, 2004; Stevens et al., 2015</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">The changes in forest floor components we measured were minimal, with marginally significant loss of duff in old-growth stands and increased litter accumulation in early-seral stands (Appendix <ce:cross-ref id="cr0655" refid="sec0110">Fig S6</ce:cross-ref>). This marginal decline in duff depth in old-growth stands may be attributed to increased decomposition rates driven by warming temperatures, while litter accumulation could be promoted by the reduced precipitation and increased canopy cover, which contributes more organic material (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0150" refid="bib14 bib20 bib49">Chojnacky et al., 2009; Dawson-Glass et al., 2023; Hopkins et al., 2012</ce:cross-refs>). These changes can influence plant establishment and regeneration by altering soil nutrient availability and substrate quality. However, they may have less impact on species that are already well established. The loss of exposed mineral soil, particularly in early-seral plots, reflects the establishment of pioneer species and the gradual buildup of duff and litter as the stand matures (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0155" refid="bib30 bib126">Feng et al., 2025; Zhao et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). This shift supports the transition from pioneer species, which typically germinate more successfully on bare soil, to forest species that are better adapted to regenerate through layers of duff and litter (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0160" refid="bib107 bib124">Tiebel et al., 2018; Xiuyu et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0085" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0105">Compositional Shifts in Understory</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">While GAMMs offer the ability to model complex non-linear relationships, they, like other non-parametric models, can be prone to overfitting (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0660" refid="bib123">Wood, 2017</ce:cross-ref>). It is worth noting that there are areas of uncertainty in the models that would impact the interpretation of the results, especially given the smaller sample size for the mature plots (<ce:italic>n</ce:italic> = 3). Despite this, the predictions in our models captured key trends in the data that are consistent with the literature, indicating a reduction in richness in early-seral plots after 18 years coinciding with increased canopy cover and stand maturation (intermediate DBH of largest trees). The model also projected declining beta diversity with stand age, reaching its lowest levels in stands with average large trees are <ce:underline>&gt;</ce:underline> 100 cm DBH (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0665" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0670" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">Our compositional results support the prediction that early-seral plots would show increasing similarity to mature plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0675" refid="tbl0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0680" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>). There were similarities in species composition of the mature and old-growth plots within each sample year, therefore, the prediction that the community of the mature stage is developing towards that of the old-growth stage is confirmed. The strong correlation of Axis 1 with the structural characteristics of old growth (i.e., large diameter trees, standing dead trees, and duff and litter accumulation) suggests that overstory structure may shape understory development (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0685" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0690" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0695" refid="bib18">D’Amato et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0700" refid="bib37">Goldblum, 1997</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0705" refid="bib71">Lindh and Muir, 2004</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0710" refid="bib95">Scheller and Mladenoff, 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0715" refid="bib100">Spies and Franklin, 1991</ce:cross-ref>). Alternatively, understory composition and overstory structure may develop in parallel.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">Beta diversity patterns in mature and old-growth stands suggest that species variation among subplots is influenced by both habitat homogeneity and species distributional patterns. Mature stands exhibited moderate beta diversity despite low richness and evenness, reflecting more patchy species distributions across subplots. This suggests that habitat conditions in mature forests—such as accumulation of coarse woody debris and microclimatic variability—create localized differences in species composition, maintaining moderate beta diversity even when overall species richness remains low. In contrast, old-growth stands exhibited lower beta-diversity despite having structural variability (coarse woody debris, canopy gaps, and larger tree size) and higher richness (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0720" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0725" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>). This is likely due to a more homogenous plant community across subplots, where a larger number of species are consistently found throughout the stand. The relatively stable environmental conditions in old-growth forests create a more uniform microclimate, and even with heterogeneous vertical and horizontal forest structure there may be reduced small-scale habitat variation, leading to subplot-level homogeneity of composition (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0730" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0735" refid="bib23">Dovčiak and Halpern, 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0740" refid="bib93">Sabatini et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The traits ordination suggests a gradient of increasing shade tolerance in plant species with stand age and canopy cover that is consistent with other studies; there were more shade-intolerant species in the early-seral stands than in the dominant species in mature and old-growth stands (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0745" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0750" refid="bib99">Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0755" refid="bib114">Valerio et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0090" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0110">Associations of indicator species with developmental stages</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">The ISA showed the loss of species with low shade tolerance (e.g. <ce:italic>Arctostaphylos glandulosa</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Ceanothus velutinus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Chamaenerion angustifolium</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Elymus glaucus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Penstemon anguineus</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Ribes sanguineum</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Rubus parviflorus</ce:italic>) in the early-seral plots in the 18-year period and a weakening of the affinity of shrubs with intermediate shade tolerance. This result supports the predictions of declining richness with the loss of early successional species as early-seral forests undergo canopy closure (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0165" refid="bib42 bib57 bib99">Halpern and Lutz, 2013; Jules et al., 2008; Smith et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>). The new indicator species for early-seral stands is little price’s pine, <ce:italic>Chimaphila menziesii</ce:italic>, a low growing clonal shrub that is present in all developmental stages, seen usually in late-succession post-fire disturbance and typically seen at highest abundance under intermediate light levels, potentially signifying this change in light availability in these plots and the time passed since disturbance (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0170" refid="bib27 bib78 bib110">Emmingham, 1972; McKenzie and Halpern, 1999; U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">The relative paucity of a significant indicator species in mature stands is likely due to overall low abundance of understory vegetation in these closed-canopy forests. Furthermore, this transitional stage is still developing distinct structural conditions (e.g., vertical and horizontal complexity, canopy heterogeneity) and both shade intolerant early-seral species and old-growth associated species are not as well represented. The majority of old-growth associated species are capable of reproduction by seed but some may not produce a flower, and therefore fruit, each growing season (i.e., <ce:italic>Trillium ovatum</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Clintonia uniflora</ce:italic>), and when they do sexually reproduce their seeds may need a particular dispersal vector (e.g., ants, birds, wasps) and/or may have low germination viability (i.e., <ce:italic>Achlys triphylla</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Lysimachia latifolia</ce:italic>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0760" refid="bib50">Ingersoll and Wilson, 1989</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0765" refid="bib70">Lindh, 2010</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0770" refid="bib110">U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0775" refid="bib54">; Jules, 1996</ce:cross-ref>). These species may have a long recovery period due to poor dispersal or a requirement for specific habitat conditions (e.g., light levels, moisture, presence of symbiotic fungi) that have not developed yet (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0780" refid="bib73">Loya and Jules, 2007</ce:cross-ref>). An example of delayed species recovery is that of the orchid <ce:italic>Goodyera oblongifolia</ce:italic>, which was completely absent in the early-seral plots of this study in the first survey in 2003, but was present in these stands 18 years later (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0785" refid="bib57">Jules et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">Our analysis suggests there are species indicative of old-growth forests in our study area (<ce:italic>Adenocaulon bicolor</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Achlys triphylla, Clintonia uniflora</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Mianthemum stellatum</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Osmorhiza berteroi)</ce:italic> and that these species persisted as indicator species between the sample years (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0790" refid="tbl0035">Table 7</ce:cross-ref>). Although sexual reproduction can occur when environmental conditions are ideal, it is more likely that these species persist through vegetative means in stable, old forests (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0175" refid="bib50 bib110 bib113">Ingersoll and Wilson, 1989; U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023; USDA NRCS, 2023</ce:cross-refs>). The relative stability of community composition in old growth and increase in cover of shade-tolerant species over time runs counter to the expectation that these species should decline as the climate warms and precipitation declines (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0795" refid="bib38">Govaert et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). However, these results are consistent with <ce:cross-ref id="cr0800" refid="bib45">Harrison et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref> observation of an increase in relative cover by species of northern biogeographic affinity at higher elevations (1500–2100 m). Understories of old-growth forests may be buffered from macro-climate fluctuations by dense canopies and multilayered forest structure (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0805" refid="bib33">Frey et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Notably, however, we observed turnover in some old-growth associated species, including the orchids, <ce:italic>Corallorhiza maculata</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Goodyera oblongifolia,</ce:italic> that did not persist as indicators of old growth. This may be indicative of the sensitivity of orchids to environmental changes, changes to forest floor components (duff and litter depth) and below ground fungal diversity these species depend on for germination and nutrition (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0180" refid="bib69 bib110">Li et al., 2021; U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2023</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0095" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0115">Implications for management and further research</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">Pre-disturbance composition of the understory layer and its persistence through disturbances plays a key role in determining the composition of the flora after events like timber harvest (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0185" refid="bib24 bib39 bib41 bib61">Duguid and Ashton, 2013; Halpern, 1988; Halpern and Franklin, 1990; Kermavnar et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). Many of the predominant species in the understory layer of late successional forests are dispersal limited and largely persist through vegetative means (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0190" refid="bib1 bib12 bib40 bib63 bib122">Abella and Springer, 2012; Carr and Krueger, 2012; Halpern et al., 1999; Koncz et al., 2010; Wódkiewicz and Kwiatkowska-Falińska, 2010</ce:cross-refs>). However, there are varying mechanisms of persistence and vegetative spread that affect the species response to disturbance, such as having a mycotrophic life history, nutritional storage in root systems that facilitates persistence, and/or root and rhizome systems that aid in expansion (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0810" refid="bib5">Antos et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0815" refid="bib67">Lezberg et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0820" refid="bib81">Moola and Vasseur, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0825" refid="bib109">Turner, 2010</ce:cross-ref>). The dependence on the community prior to disturbance leads to concerns that the practice of short-rotations harvests (30–80 years) that does not allow sufficient time for understory reinitiation may lead to further attrition of species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0195" refid="bib59 bib108">Kahmen and Jules, 2005; Tinya et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0290" view="all">Management practices that are less intensive than clearcutting, such as gap creation and uneven-age thinning, have been seen to have fewer negative impacts on forest floor conditions and therefore the reestablishment of understory composition (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0200" refid="bib6 bib24 bib34 bib51 bib61 bib108">Bailey et al., 1998; Duguid and Ashton, 2013; Fujii et al., 2021; Johnson et al., 2023; Kermavnar et al., 2021; Tinya et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Although this study did not directly examine the effects of natural fire regimes, it is important to note that the reintroduction of fire in western mixed conifer forests has been shown to restore forest structure and enhance understory herb richness and cover—especially when combined with thinning treatments (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0205" refid="bib82 bib119">Odland et al., 2021; Wayman and North, 2007</ce:cross-refs>). To better understand the drivers of change or stability in these understory communities, further research is needed. This could include more comprehensive forest stand inventories, localized climate monitoring (e.g., air and soil temperature and moisture), reconstructing the disturbance chronology with tree rings, and the inclusion of plots that have experienced documented wildfire disturbance. These additions would provide finer-scale insights into the factors shaping plant community dynamics. Given that fire is a well-documented ecological driver in the study region, incorporating its effects into future research is equally as important as considering climate change.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0100" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0120">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">Our study demonstrates the legacy effects of clearcut logging and potentially climate change on a critical component of forest biodiversity. As young, post-harvest stands (25–60 year old) transition to conditions characterized by high canopy cover, our results point towards declining understory species richness and diversity across a significant portion of the Pacific Northwest landscape. Beta diversity was highest in early-seral stands and declined with stand age, a pattern that remained consistent across sampling periods. In old-growth stands, increases in a few dominant shade-tolerant species drove declines in evenness and diversity, a pattern that partially aligns with expectations of increased drought-tolerant species under rising temperatures and reduced precipitation. While these species are typically associated with shaded, moist forest conditions, they are not strictly drought-intolerant, suggesting a more complex response to changing climate conditions. Understanding whether managed stands are developing toward conditions that support understory recovery is essential for maintaining biodiversity and forest resilience (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0210" refid="bib28 bib53">Falk et al., 2022; Johnstone et al., 2010</ce:cross-refs>). Recognizing the influence of management and successional dynamics on understory plant communities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0215" refid="bib35 bib51 bib101">Gaines et al., 2022; Johnson et al., 2023; Spies et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>) can be useful while revaluating the management strategies for forests under the Northwest Forest Plan (NWFP). The current threat to the protection of old-growth forests under the NWFP, coupled with the potential for renewed intensive logging, emphasizes the significance of management decisions for understory communities, where the majority of forest plant diversity is found. In our study region, the compounded effects of habitat loss and climate change are likely to accelerate declines in understory species richness and diversity. Safeguarding these forests is essential—not only for preserving biodiversity, but also for maintaining the long-term resilience of forest ecosystems in the face of ongoing environmental change.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0125">Declaration of Competing interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0300" view="all">The authors declare the following financial interests/personal relationships which may be considered as potential competing interests: Molly B. Smith Metok reports financial support was provided by Native Plant Society of Oregon. If there are other authors, they declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0130">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0305" view="all">We extend gratitude to A. Kahmen for his foundational fieldwork that we built this study upon, and to K. Byrne and C. Cuellar-Gempeler (Cal Poly Humboldt University), as well as Jeňýk Hofmeister (Czech University of Life Sciences), for their ecological and editorial insight and advice. We thank those who helped with planning (L. McCrigler, S. Morrison, and T. Hooker) and collecting field data (J. Ingalls, C. Copper, and J. Felt). Statistical code and advice were provided by P. Bourdeau, A. Buchheister, R. Overholser, and G. Simpson. Financial support was provided by the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Native Plant Society of Oregon, Cal Poly Humboldt RSCA</ce:grant-sponsor>, <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Biology Graduate Student Association</ce:grant-sponsor>, and the <ce:grant-sponsor id="spnsr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Czech University of Life Sciences</ce:grant-sponsor> grant IGA (<ce:grant-number refid="spnsr3">A_18_25</ce:grant-number>).</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
